---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title = "What You Need to Stream on Nile: Phones, Cameras & Gear | Nile";
const description =
  "Every device that works with Nile: recommended iPhones, Android phones, iPads, and Macs, plus external mics, audio mixers, and cameras that plug right in.";

const articleSchema = JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "TechArticle",
  headline: "Get the Most Out of Nile: Compatible Devices & Gear",
  description,
  author: { "@type": "Organization", name: "Nile" },
  publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: "Nile" },
});
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonical="/resources/compatible-devices"
  jsonLd={articleSchema}
>
  <!-- HERO / INTRO -->
  <section class="hero nile-section">
    <div class="nile-container hero-inner">
      <p class="nile-eyebrow">Device Guide</p>
      <h1>Get the most out of Nile.</h1>
      <p class="nile-lead">
        Getting started on Nile is simple: all you need is a smartphone. Mount
        it, go live, and you're streaming a ticketed show. But if you want to
        level up (more angles, better sound, bigger production), here's every
        device we recommend, and exactly how to connect it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- DEVICES THAT RUN THE APP -->
  <section class="band nile-section">
    <div class="nile-container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="nile-eyebrow">Run the app</p>
        <h2>Devices that run Nile</h2>
        <p class="section-sub">
          Live multi-angle streaming asks a lot of a device. Older hardware may
          technically run the app, but these are the devices we recommend for a
          stream that never makes you think about the stream.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="device-grid">
        <div class="device-card">
          <h3>Smartphones</h3>
          <p>
            Your phone is a full Nile camera. Most shows are made entirely
            with phones. Two friends, two phones, two angles: that's a
            production.
          </p>
          <ul class="device-list">
            <li>iPhone 12 and later, running iOS 16 or newer</li>
            <li>Google Pixel 7 and later</li>
            <li>Samsung Galaxy S21 and later</li>
            <li>Other Android flagships from 2022 on, running Android 12+</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="device-card">
          <h3>Tablets</h3>
          <p>
            An iPad makes a great locked-off wide shot or a roomy screen for
            running your show. We recommend and test on iPad. The app runs on
            Android tablets too, but iPad is where we make sure everything just
            works.
          </p>
          <ul class="device-list">
            <li>iPad (10th generation) and later</li>
            <li>iPad Air and iPad Pro models with USB-C</li>
            <li>iPadOS 17 or newer if you plan to plug in an external camera</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="device-card">
          <h3>Mac</h3>
          <p>
            The Nile app on Mac turns your desk into a control room: a bigger
            screen for managing cameras, chat, and your crew mid-show.
          </p>
          <ul class="device-list">
            <li>Any Apple silicon Mac (M1 and later)</li>
            <li>macOS 13 Ventura or newer</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- EXTERNAL DEVICES: AUDIO -->
  <section class="nile-section">
    <div class="nile-container split">
      <div class="split-head">
        <p class="nile-eyebrow">External devices</p>
        <h2>Better sound, simply.</h2>
        <p class="seo-h2">External microphones and audio mixers for live streaming</p>
      </div>
      <div class="split-body">
        <h3>Microphones</h3>
        <p>
          Your phone's built-in mic is good. A dedicated mic is the single
          biggest upgrade you can make. Plug one in and Nile detects it
          automatically. Just switch on <strong>external mic mode</strong> in
          the camera screen so your mic's own sound passes through untouched.
        </p>
        <ul class="device-list">
          <li>Plug-in mics: Rode VideoMic GO II, Shure MV88+ (USB-C)</li>
          <li>Wireless kits: Rode Wireless GO II, DJI Mic 2</li>
          <li>Any USB-C microphone your phone or iPad recognizes</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Audio mixers</h3>
        <p>
          Already running sound through a mixing board? You can send that mix
          straight into your stream. Take a line out from the mixer into a
          small USB audio interface (or Apple's USB-C-to-3.5mm adapter), plug
          that into the phone or iPad acting as your main camera, and Nile
          treats it like an external mic. Turn on external mic mode and your
          board's mix (every instrument, every voice) is what the audience
          hears.
        </p>
        <ul class="device-list">
          <li>Any mixer with a line/monitor output</li>
          <li>
            Connect via a USB audio interface (e.g. Behringer UCA202, Focusrite
            Scarlett Solo) or Apple's USB-C audio adapter
          </li>
          <li>Keep the mixer's output level low to start, then raise it during sound check</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- EXTERNAL DEVICES: VIDEO -->
  <section class="band nile-section">
    <div class="nile-container split">
      <div class="split-head">
        <p class="nile-eyebrow">External devices</p>
        <h2>More ways to get the shot.</h2>
        <p class="seo-h2">External cameras and capture cards for live streaming</p>
      </div>
      <div class="split-body">
        <h3>External cameras on Mac</h3>
        <p>
          On a Mac, Nile isn't limited to the built-in camera. Pick any
          connected camera right from the camera screen.
        </p>
        <ul class="device-list">
          <li>USB webcams: Logitech Brio, Insta360 Link, or any standard webcam</li>
          <li>
            HDMI cameras (DSLRs, mirrorless, camcorders) via a capture card
            like the Elgato Cam Link 4K (the camera shows up as a webcam)
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>External cameras on iPad <span class="soon-chip">Rolling out soon</span></h3>
        <p>
          On iPads with USB-C running iPadOS 17 or newer, you'll be able to
          plug in a USB webcam and use it as your Nile camera, great for
          mounting a proper camera while the iPad stays at the operator's
          station.
        </p>

        <h3>Screen sharing <span class="soon-chip">Rolling out soon</span></h3>
        <p>
          Share your Mac or iPad screen into the stream as its own tile
          alongside the cameras: slides for a talk, lyrics for worship,
          gameplay for a watch party. Viewers switch to it like any other
          angle.
        </p>

        <p class="fine-note">
          Phones stream from their built-in cameras. And honestly, that's the
          point. The best external camera setup still starts with a couple of
          phones.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CLOSING CTA -->
  <section class="closing nile-section">
    <div class="nile-container closing-inner">
      <h2>Start with the phone in your pocket.</h2>
      <p class="closing-sub">
        Everything on this page is optional. A smartphone and something worth
        showing. That's a Nile event.
      </p>
      <a href="/host" class="nile-btn nile-btn--primary">Host Your First Event →</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  h2 {
    margin-bottom: var(--nile-s-2);
  }
  .seo-h2 {
    color: var(--nile-txt-tertiary);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    margin-bottom: var(--nile-s-4);
  }

  /* Hero */
  .hero {
    padding-block: var(--nile-s-16) var(--nile-s-12);
  }
  .hero-inner {
    max-width: 720px;
  }

  /* Device grid */
  .section-head {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin-bottom: var(--nile-s-8);
  }
  .section-sub {
    color: var(--nile-txt-secondary);
  }
  .device-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: var(--nile-s-6);
  }
  .device-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--nile-border);
    border-radius: var(--nile-r-lg);
    padding: var(--nile-s-6);
  }
  .device-card h3 {
    margin-bottom: var(--nile-s-3);
  }
  .device-card p {
    color: var(--nile-txt-secondary);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    margin-bottom: var(--nile-s-4);
  }

  /* Shared list style */
  .device-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--nile-s-6);
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--nile-s-2);
  }
  .device-list li {
    color: var(--nile-txt-secondary);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    padding-left: var(--nile-s-5);
    position: relative;
  }
  .device-list li::before {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0.55em;
    width: 8px;
    height: 8px;
    border-radius: 2px;
    background: var(--nile-volt);
  }

  /* Split */
  .split {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1.4fr;
    gap: var(--nile-s-12);
    align-items: start;
  }
  .split-head h2 {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  .split-body p {
    color: var(--nile-txt-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--nile-s-4);
  }
  .split-body h3 {
    margin-bottom: var(--nile-s-2);
  }
  .split-body h3:not(:first-child) {
    margin-top: var(--nile-s-6);
  }

  .soon-chip {
    display: inline-block;
    vertical-align: middle;
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--nile-volt) 50%, transparent);
    border-radius: var(--nile-r-pill);
    padding: 2px var(--nile-s-3);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--nile-volt);
    margin-left: var(--nile-s-2);
  }
  .fine-note {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--nile-txt-tertiary);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--nile-border);
    padding-top: var(--nile-s-4);
    margin-top: var(--nile-s-6);
  }

  /* Closing */
  .closing-inner {
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 600px;
  }
  .closing-sub {
    color: var(--nile-txt-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--nile-s-6);
  }

  @media (max-width: 880px) {
    .device-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
    .split {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: var(--nile-s-8);
    }
  }
</style>
